library(expsmooth)
library(knitr)
library(tidyverse)
library(tseries)
library(TSA)
library(xts)
library(lubridate)
library(timetk)
sales <- read_csv("Metro_median_sale_price_uc_SFRCondo_raw_week.csv") #Import Data
US_median<-sales[1,6:ncol(sales)] #Get only weekly sales data
Dallas_median<-sales[5,6:ncol(sales)]
LA_median<-sales[3,6:ncol(sales)]
Chicago_median<-sales[4,6:ncol(sales)]
US_sales <- US_median %>% gather(key = "Date", value = "Price") %>%select(Date, Price) # SEt-up sales data for each city
Dallas_sales <- Dallas_median %>% gather(key = "Date", value = "Price") %>%select(Date, Price) 
LA_sales <- LA_median %>% gather(key = "Date", value = "Price") %>%select(Date, Price) 
Chicago_sales <- Chicago_median %>% gather(key = "Date", value = "Price") %>%select(Date, Price) 

US_sales$Date<-as.POSIXct(US_sales$Date, format="%Y-%m-%d") #Convert Dates to POSIXct
Dallas_sales$Date<-as.POSIXct(Dallas_sales$Date, format="%Y-%m-%d")
LA_sales$Date<-as.POSIXct(LA_sales$Date, format="%Y-%m-%d")
Chicago_sales$Date<-as.POSIXct(Chicago_sales$Date, format="%Y-%m-%d")
US_TS<-xts(US_sales$Price, order.by = US_sales$Date) #Create xts object
Dallas_TS<-xts(Dallas_sales$Price, order.by = Dallas_sales$Date)
LA_TS<-xts(LA_sales$Price, order.by = LA_sales$Date)
Chicago_TS<-xts(Chicago_sales$Price, order.by = Chicago_sales$Date)

attr(US_TS, 'frequency') <- 52 #Set frequency to 1 year (52 weeks)
attr(Dallas_TS, 'frequency') <- 52
attr(LA_TS, 'frequency') <- 52
attr(Chicago_TS, 'frequency') <- 52

Here we are only using data after the Great Recession was over. We need to discuss if this is appropriate (Im not sure). But I think this was such a massive change in the housing market that its possible the fundamental principles of housing prices changed and the data from durring the recession is not useful. TBD.

US_train<-window(US_TS,start = "2014-08-23", end = "2019-08-24") #Splitting to Train and Test
US_test<-window(US_TS,start = "2019-08-31")

Dallas_train<-window(Dallas_TS,start = "2014-08-23", end = "2019-08-24")
Dallas_test<-window(Dallas_TS,start = "2019-08-31")

LA_train<-window(LA_TS,start = "2014-08-23", end = "2019-08-24")
LA_test<-window(LA_TS,start = "2019-08-31")

Chicago_train<-window(Chicago_TS,start = "2014-08-23", end = "2019-08-24")
Chicago_test<-window(Chicago_TS,start = "2019-08-31")

Create ARIMA models

md_US<-auto.arima(US_train,d=1)
md_Dallas<-auto.arima(Dallas_train,d=1)
md_LA<-auto.arima(LA_train,d=1)
md_Chicago<-auto.arima(Chicago_train,d=1)

Provide anaylsis of the different (p,d,q)(P,D,Q) levels for each model.
